step.tex:
y =  \left(\tan^{-1} x\right)^2\\
\begin{align}
		\dfrac{dy}{dx} &= \dfrac{d \left(\left(\tan^{-1} x\right)^2\right)}{dx}\\
							&= \underbrace{2 \tan^{-1} x . \left(\dfrac{d \left(\tan^{-1} x \right)}{dx}\right)}_{Chain Rule}\\
							&= 2 \tan^{-1} x . \left(\dfrac{1}{1 + x^2}\right)
\end{align}

y =  \left(\tan^{-1} x\right)^2\\
\begin{align}
		\dfrac{dy}{dx} &= \dfrac{d \left( \left(\tan^{-1} x\right)^2\right)}{dx}= \underbrace{2  \left(\dfrac{d \left(\tan^{-1} x \right)}{dx}\right)}_{Chain Rule}\\
							&= \dfrac{2}{1 + x^2}
\end{align}

step.reason:
\text{We have used Chain Rule and the fact that}\\
\dfrac{d \left(\sin \theta\right)}{d\theta} = \cos \theta \text{ and }\dfrac{d \left(\cos \theta\right)}{d\theta} = -\sin \theta.\\
\text{Review Chain Rule if you got it wrong.}

\text{Other than Chain Rule we have used the  }\\
\text{fact that }\dfrac{d \left(\tan^{-1} x\right)}{dx} = \dfrac{1}{1 + x^2}\text{.Check your}\\
\text{calculations if you something else.}
